{"title_page": "2015 in Wales", "text_new": "{{Year in Wales header|2015}}\nThis article is about the particular significance of the year '''2015''' to [[Wales]] and [[Welsh people|its people]].\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[Prince of Wales]] \u2013 [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Charles]]\n*[[Princess of Wales]] \u2013 [[Camilla, Duchess of Cornwall]] (does not use title)\n*[[First Minister of Wales|First Minister]] \u2013 [[Carwyn Jones]]\n*[[Secretary of State for Wales]] \u2013 [[David Jones (MP for Clwyd West)|David Jones]] (until 14 July); [[Stephen Crabb]] (from 15 July)\n*[[Archbishop of Wales]] \u2013 [[Barry Morgan]], [[Bishop of Llandaff]]\n*[[Archdruid]] of the [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]] \u2013 [[Christine James]]\n\n==Events==\n*[[9 January]] - Strong winds cause damage and disruption in parts of Wales, as trees are blown down, electricity supplies interrupted, and flood warnings issued.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-30759477 BBC News - \"Gales cause damage and disruption across Wales\", 10 January 2015]. Accessed 11 January 2015</ref>  Three children from [[Ysgol Gyfun Gwynllyw]] are injured when a falling tree hits their school bus.\n*[[31 January]] \u2013 The head of the [[Police Federation of England and Wales]] expresses his controversial support for all front-line police officers in England and Wales to be offered [[Tasers]] in light of the increased terrorism threat to the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-31071922 |title='Tasers for all front-line officers' \u2013 Police Federation |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=31 January 2015 |accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n*[[4 February]] \u2013 The ferryboat service between [[D\u00fan Laoghaire]] in Ireland and [[Holyhead]] ends after 204 years. The boat from [[Dublin Port]] to Holyhead remains in service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2015/0204/677847-dun-laoghaire-holyhead-ferry-ends-after-204-years/|title=Dun Laoghaire-Holyhead ferry ends after 204 years|work=RT\u00c9 News|date=4 February 2015|accessdate=4 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226171548/http://www.rte.ie/news/2015/0204/677847-dun-laoghaire-holyhead-ferry-ends-after-204-years/|archivedate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n*[[12 February]] - Health minister [[Mark Drakeford]] announces a ban on smoking in cars carrying children, with effect from 1 October.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-31418599 BBC News - \"Wales smoking ban in cars with children from October\"]. Accessed 15 February 2015</ref>\n*[[26 February]] - Gwent Police and social services apologise for their failure to prevent three murders carried out by Carl Mills in Cwmbran in September 2012.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-south-east-wales-31632416 BBC News - \"Gwent Police failed Carl Mills murder victims - reports\", 26 February 2015]</ref>  \n*[[6 March]] - Seven teenagers are arrested for dangerous driving following an accident on the [[A470]] near [[Pen y Fan#Storey Arms|Storey Arms]], in which four people were killed.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-31782700 BBC News - Inquiry continues after four killed in A470 Storey Arms crash, 8 March 2015]. Accessed 15 March 2015</ref>\n*[[18 March]] - A document confirming [[Henry Gower]]'s consecration as [[Bishop of St David's]] in [[1328 in Wales|1328]] goes up for auction at Bonham's, where it is expected to fetch between \u00a34,000 and \u00a36,000.<ref>[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/historic-document-helped-rise-cleric-8704045 \"Historic document which helped the rise of the cleric behind a ruined Welsh palace is up for auction\", Wales Online, 23 February 2015]. Accessed 26 February 2015</ref>\n*[[31 March]] - [[Plaid Cymru]] launches its election manifesto in Bangor.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2015-32127047BBC News - \"Plaid Cymru manifesto calls for end to austerity\"]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Accessed 1 April 2015</ref>\n*[[1 April]] - During a televised election debate, Plaid Cymru leader [[Leanne Wood]] tells UKIP leader [[Nigel Farage]] that he should be ashamed of himself for his comments about AIDS patients from overseas.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/general-election-leaders-debate-you-should-be-ashamed-of-yourself-farage-told-as-he-lashes-out-at-foreigners-with-hiv-10153615.html \"TV leaders' debate: \u2018You should be ashamed of yourself\u2019 Farage told as he lashes out at foreigners with HIV\", ''The Independent'', 2 April 2015]. Accessed 4 May 2015</ref>\n*[[3 May]] - The [[Royal Mint]] announces the issue of a special silver penny to celebrate the birth of [[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge]], daughter of the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-32563357 BBC News, \"Royal baby: Royal Mint gifts babies with silver penny\"]. Accessed 3 May 2015</ref>\n*[[8 May]] - In the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|United Kingdom general election]], the Conservative Party wins three additional seats in Wales:<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/election-2015-wales-32574458 BBC News - Election Results: Wales]. Accessed 8 May 2015</ref>\n**[[Byron Davies]] wins [[Gower (UK Parliament constituency)|Gower]] from Labour.\n**[[James Davies (politician)|James Davies]] wins [[Vale of Clwyd (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Clwyd]] from Labour.\n**[[Christopher Davies (Conservative politician)|Chris Davies]] wins [[Brecon and Radnorshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Brecon and Radnorshire]] from the Liberal Democrats.<ref>[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/general-election-2015-9-key-9211465 Wales Online - \"The Conservatives also made key gains in Vale of Clwyd (from Labour) and Brecon and Radnorshire (from the Lib Dems)\"]. Accessed 8 May 2015</ref>\n**[[Jo Stevens]] wins [[Cardiff Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Cardiff Central]] for Labour from the Liberal Democrats.\n**[[Liz Saville Roberts]] becomes [[Plaid Cymru]]'s first woman MP, when she retains [[Dwyfor Meirionnydd (UK Parliament constituency)|Dwyfor Meirionnydd]] for the party.<ref>[http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/general-election-2015-dwyfor-meirionnydd-9206088 \"General Election 2015: Dwyfor Meirionnydd - Liz Saville Roberts becomes Plaid's first ever elected woman MP\", ''Daily Post'']. Accessed 8 May 2015</ref>\n*[[12 June]] - Welsh people recognised in the [[2015 Birthday Honours]] include rugby player [[Gareth Edwards]]<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/33109354 BBC Sport - \"Queen's Birthday Honours: Gareth Edwards receives knighthood\"]. Accessed 13 June 2015</ref> and composer [[Karl Jenkins]], who receive knighthoods, and singer [[Michael Ball (singer)|Michael Ball]] (CBE).\n*[[21 June]] - [[Nadine Koutcher]] wins the 2015 [[BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition]].<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC Cardiff Singer of the World winner is crowned|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-33213145|website=bbc.com|publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n*[[3 July]]\n**[[Drift mining]] is suspended at [[Aberpergwm]], the last substantial coal mine in Wales.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/jobs-coal-mothballed/story-26768464-detail/story.html|title=Jobs to go as South West Wales coal mine is mothballed|work=[[South Wales Evening Post]]|date=2015-06-26|accessdate=2016-08-20}}</ref>\n**The [[Abolish the Welsh Assembly Party]] is founded by a Bridgend businessman and former UKIP member.<ref>[http://search.electoralcommission.org.uk/api/pdf/Registrations/PP2802  Registration:Abolish The Welsh Assembly Party, ''Electoral Commission'']. Retrieved 2 May 2016</ref>\n*[[20 August|20]]-[[23 August]] - The annual [[Green Man Festival]] is headlined by [[St. Vincent (musician)|St Vincent]], [[Super Furry Animals]] and [[Hot Chip]].\n*[[18 November]] - Two workers are killed in an explosion at the Celsa Steel works in Splott.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cardiff steelworks explosion: Two dead and five injured|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-south-east-wales-34862540|website=bbc.com|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n*[[1 December]] - Wales becomes the first nation in the UK to introduce a scheme for organ donation, whereby adults are regarded as consenting to become donors unless they have opted-out.<ref>{{cite web|title=Organ donation law 'revolution' starts in Wales|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-34964382|website=bbc.com|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[30 December]] - Power distribution companies report that 1400 homes have suffered prolonged power losses as [[Storm Frank]] affects Wales.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-35192785 BBC News - \"Wales weather: 1,400 lose power as Storm Frank hits\"]. Accessed 30 December 2015</ref>\n*[[31 December]] - Welsh nominees in the [[New Year Honours]] List include actress [[Sian Phillips]] (DBE) and broadcaster [[Simon Weston]] (CBE).<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/489049/NY2016HonoursFullList.pdf New Year Honours List]</ref>\n\n==Arts and literature==\n\n===Welsh Awards===\n*[[Glynd\u0175r Award]] \n*National Eisteddfod of Wales: Chair \u2013 [[Hywel Griffiths]]<ref name=\"Daily2015\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/national-eisteddfod-meifod-chair-ceremony-9815357 |title=The National Eisteddfod chair awarded to Hywel Griffiths from Aberystwyth|publisher=BBC News|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015|author=Crump, Eryl}}</ref>\n*National Eisteddfod of Wales: Crown \u2013 [[Manon Rhys]], \"Breuddwyd\"\n*National Eisteddfod of Wales: Prose Medal \u2013 [[Tony Bianchi]]<ref>[http://www.eisteddfod.org.uk/english/2015/2015-news/?request=156250 2015 News: The National Eisteddfod]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Accessed 30 December 2015</ref>\n*Gwobr Goffa Daniel Owen: Mari Lisa<ref>[http://www.eisteddfod.org.uk/english/2015/2015-news/?request=156252 2015 News: The National Eisteddfod, \"Mari Lisa wins the Daniel Owen Memorial Prize\"]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Accessed 30 December 2015</ref>\n*[[Wales Book of the Year]]: \n**English language: [[Patrick McGuinness]] ''Other People's Countries'' ([[Jonathan Cape]])<ref name=\"BBC2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-33010037 |title=Patrick McGuinness wins second Welsh Book of the Year award|publisher=BBC News|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n***Fiction: [[Cynan Jones]] ''The Dig'' (Granta)\n***Non-fiction: [[Patrick McGuinness]] ''Other People's Countries'' ([[Jonathan Cape]])\n***Poetry: [[Tiffany Atkinson]] - ''So Many Moving Parts'' (Bloodaxe Books)\n**Welsh language: [[Gareth F. Williams]] ''Awst yn Anogia'' (Gwasg Gwynedd)<ref name=\"BBC2015\"/>\n***Fiction: [[Gareth F. Williams]] ''Awst yn Anogia'' (Gwasg Gwynedd)\n***Non-fiction: [[Ll\u0177r Gwyn Lewis]] ''Rhyw Flodau Rhyfel'' (Y Lolfa). \n***Poetry: [[Rhys Iorwerth]] ''Un Stribedyn Bach'' (Gwasg Carreg Gwalch)\n\n===New books===\n\n====English language====\n*[[Lorin Morgan-Richards]] - ''Welsh in the Old West''\n*[[Meic Stephens]] - ''My Shoulder to the Wheel''\n\n====Welsh language====\n*[[:cy:Zonia Bowen|Zonia Bowen]] - ''Dy bobl di fydd fy mhobl i''\n\n===Music===\n====Awards====\n*[[Welsh Music Prize]] \u2013 [[Gwenno]], ''Y Dydd Olaf''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-34932959 |title=Gwenno wins Welsh Music Prize 2015 |accessdate=29 November 2015|date=26 November 2015|publisher=BBC Wales}}</ref>\n\n====Albums====\n*[[Catrin Finch]] - ''Tides''\n*[[Karl Jenkins]] - ''The Healer - A Cantata for St Luke''\n\n===Film===\n*''No Manifesto - A Film About Manic Street Preachers''<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/29/no-manifesto-a-film-about-manic-street-preachers-review \"No Manifesto: A Film About Manic Street Preachers review \u2013 intelligent fan\u2019s-eye-view\", ''The Guardian, 29 January 2015]. Accessed 11 February 2016</ref>\n*''[[Under Milk Wood (2015 film)|Under Milk Wood]]'', directed by [[Kevin Allen (actor)|Kevin Allen]]\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:2015 World Cup - Rugby ball at Cardiff Castle.jpg|thumb|250px|As part of the 2015 Rugby World Cup, Cardiff Castle displays a mock giant rugby ball breaking through its walls.]]\n*[[Track and field|Athletics]]\n**[[29 October]] - [[Aled Davies (field athlete)|Aled Davies]] wins his second gold medal at the [[2015 IPC Athletics World Championships]] in Doha with a world record throw in the T42 discus to add to his shot put title won on the first day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/34665258|title=IPC Athletics World Championships: Aled Davies talks gold|date=29 October 2015|accessdate=31 October 2015|work=BBC sport}}</ref>\n*[[Boxing]]\n**[[30 May]] - [[Lee Selby]] becomes IBF Featherweight Champion after beating Russia's [[Evgeny Gradovich]] on points in London. Selby becomes the 12th Welshman to hold a world boxing title.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/boxing/32948199|title=Lee Selby wins world title but Kevin Mitchell misses out|accessdate=31 May 2015|date=30 May 2015|author=Dirs, Ben|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n**[[16 August]] - [[Joseph Cordina]] wins lightweight gold at the [[2015 European Amateur Boxing Championships|European Amateur Boxing Championships]] in [[Samokov]], Bulgaria.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/boxing/33946952|title=European Boxing: Joe Cordina wins lightweight gold|accessdate=16 August 2015|date=16 August 2015|author=McDaid, David|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n**[[15 October]] - In his debut fight in America, Lee Selby makes a successful first defense of his Featherweight Championship title against Mexico's [[Fernando Montiel]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/wales/34525496|title=Lee Selby retains IBF title in scrappy win over Fernando Montiel|accessdate=25 November 2015|date=15 October 2015|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n*[[Cricket]]\n**[[8 July]] - The [[2015 Ashes series]] opens at [[Sophia Gardens (cricket ground)|Sophia Gardens]] in Cardiff.\n*[[Cycling]]\n**[[27 March]] - [[Geraint Thomas]] wins the [[E3 Harelbeke]] race and becomes the first Welsh cyclist to win a [[Classic cycle races|classic cycle race]] in [[Arthur Linton|119 years]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Geraint Thomas: Team Sky rider wins E3 Harelbeke in Belgium|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/32093178|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n**[[13 September]] - [[Owain Doull]] finishes third, the highest ranked British racer, at the [[2015 Tour of Britain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cycling/34239340 |title=Tour of Britain: Edvald Boasson Hagen claims race win |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 September 2015 |accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Association football|Football]]\n**[[9 January]] - [[Cardiff City F.C.]]'s owner, [[Vincent Tan]], meets supporters and agrees to a return to the traditional blue playing strip, saying his mother helped him come to the decision.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-south-east-wales-30751318 BBC News - \"Cardiff City mark return to blue with win against Fulham\", 10 January 2015]. Accessed 11 January 2015</ref>\n**[[4 July]] - [[Mark Sampson]] leads the [[England women's national football team]] to third place in the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup]], the team's highest finish.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lauletta|first1=Dan|title=Bassett starts, England beats Germany for 3rd place|url=http://equalizersoccer.com/2015/07/04/bassett-starts-england-beats-germany-for-3rd-place/|accessdate=22 December 2015|publisher=The Equalizer|date=5 July 2015}}</ref>\n**[[9 July]] - The [[Wales national football team]] are ranked as the 10th best team in the world, surpassing their previous highest ranking of 22nd.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifa rankings: Wales enter world top 10 for first time|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33458794 |website=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 July 2015|date=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n**[[10 October]] - The [[Wales national football team]] qualify for the final tournament of the [[UEFA Euro 2016|2016 European football championship]], the team's first qualification for a major tournament finals since 1958.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wales qualify for Euros despite loss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34498127|archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20151012000524mp_/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34498127|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 October 2015|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 October 2015}}</ref>\n**[[9 December]] - [[Swansea City A.F.C.]] part company with manager [[Garry Monk]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Garry Monk: Swansea City part company with manager|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34762862|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 December 2015|date=9 December 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Horse racing]]\n**[[25 April]] - Welsh [[jockey]] [[Sean Bowen]] wins the British [[conditional jockey]] championship, becoming the first 17-year-old to win the title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Conditional Championship: Sean Bowen wins young jockey title|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/wales/32438170|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n**[[27 December]] - The [[Welsh Grand National]] 2015 is postponed until January 2016 because of continuous heavy rain affecting the [[Chepstow]] course.<ref>[http://www.racingbetter.co.uk/race/chepstow/welsh_national.html Racing Better - Coral Welsh National 2015]. Accessed 6 January 2016</ref>\n*[[Rallying]]\n**[[15 November]] - [[Sebastien Ogier]] wins his third successive [[Wales Rally GB]].<ref>{{cite web|title=World Rally Championship: Sebastien Ogier wins Wales Rally GB|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/wales/34826941|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 November 2015|date=15 November 2015|author=Williams, Aled}}</ref>\n*[[Rugby league]]\n**[[7 November]] - [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] win the [[2015 European Cup]], remaining unbeaten in all three matches of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/other-sport/rugby-league/wales-rugby-league-stars-crowned-10407196|title=Wales rugby league stars crowned European champions |work=walesonline.co.uk|date=8 November 2015|accessdate=20 December 2015}}</ref>  \n*[[Rugby union]]\n**[[22 March]] - [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] finish third in the [[2015 Six Nations Championship]], in a very close tournament that saw winners Ireland, England and Wales separated by ten points difference.<ref>{{cite web|title=Six Nations 2015: Ireland win title from England & Wales|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/32004426|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 October 2015}}</ref>\n**[[19 September]] - The [[Millennium Stadium]] hosts Ireland vs. Canada, the stadium's first match as part of the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]], the only venue to be used outside the host country of England.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rugby World Cup 2015: Robbie Henshaw out of Ireland opener|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/34280439|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n**[[17 October]] - Wales are knocked out of the 2015 Rugby World Cup, losing 23-19 to South Africa in the quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rugby World Cup 2015: South Africa 23-19 Wales |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/34548763|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=18 September 2015|date=17 October 2015|author=Williams, Richard}}</ref> \n*[[Snooker]]\n**[[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] wins the [[2015 Welsh Open (snooker)|2015 Welsh Open]]. [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]] is the highest ranked Welsh player, going out in the semi-finals.\n*[[Table tennis]]\n**[[14 October]] \u2013 Para table tennis player [[Rob Davies (table tennis)|Rob Davies]] retains his European title in the final of the 2015 European Open in Denmark.<ref name=\"Table tennis\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/wales/34564548 |title=Rob Davies claims second European gold in para table tennis |date=17 October 2015|publisher=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n**[[17 October]] - Welsh duo, Rob Davies and [[Tom Matthews (table tennis)|Tom Matthews]] take gold in the team para table tennis European Championships.<ref name=\"Table tennis\"/>\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\n===English-language television===\n*''[[Michael Sheen]]'s Valleys Rebellion''<ref>[http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/hollywood-star-michael-sheen-gets-8678828 \"Hollywood star Michael Sheen gets really, REALLY serious\", Wales Online, 20 February 2015]. Accessed 25 February 2015</ref>\n*''Patagonia with [[Huw Edwards (journalist)|Huw Edwards]]''<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/celebritytravel/11642833/Huw-Edwardss-Travelling-Life.html \"Huw Edwards\u2019s Travelling Life\", ''The Telegraph'', 1 June 2015]. Accessed 2 June 2015</ref>\n\n===Welsh-language television===\n*''Dan y Wenallt''<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-30528338 BBC News - \"New Welsh language film of Dylan Thomas's Under Milk Wood\"]. Accessed 25 February 2015</ref>\n*''Parch''<ref>[http://www.s4c.cymru/caban/?p=11701&lang=en \"A vicar who\u2019s dying to live \u2013 new Sunday drama on S4C\", S4C]. Accessed 29 June 2015</ref>\n*''Patagonia [[Huw Edwards (journalist)|Huw Edwards]]''<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/bbc-wales-patagonia-landmark \"BBC Wales celebrates Patagonia landmark\"]. Accessed 2 June 2015</ref>\n\n==Births==\n*[[2 May]] \u2013 [[Princess Charlotte of Cambridge]], second grandchild of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]]\n\n==Deaths==\n*[[8 January]] \u2013 [[Richard Meade]], equestrian, three-time Olympic champion, 76<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/wales/25666058 Obituary: Triple Olympic gold-medallist Richard Meade]</ref>\n*[[12 January]] \u2013 [[Paul Morgan (rugby)|Paul Morgan]], Welsh rugby union and rugby league footballer, 40<ref>[http://www.walesrugbyleague.co.uk/article/12741/rip-paul-morgan RIP Paul Morgan]</ref>\n*[[30 January]] \u2013 [[Howard Norris]], Wales and British Lions rugby union footballer, 80<ref>{{cite web|title=Wales and Lions prop Howard Norris dies|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/wales/rugby/story/254445.html|website=espn.co.uk|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n*[[12 February]] \u2013 [[Steve Strange]], singer ([[Visage (band)|Visage]] and [[Strange Cruise]]), 55<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-31449838 BBC News, \"Steve Strange, Visage lead singer, dies aged 55\", 13 February 2015]. Accessed 15 Feb 2015</ref>\n*[[14 February]] \u2013 [[Maureen Guy]], mezzo-soprano, 82\n*[[16 February]] \u2013 [[John Davies (historian)|John Davies]], historian, 76<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-31484879 Historian and BBC commentator John Davies dies aged 76]</ref>\n*[[21 February]] \u2013 [[Meredydd Evans]], professor, musician and television producer, 95<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-31567287 Former BBC Wales man Dr Meredydd Evans dies aged 95]</ref>\n*[[23 February]] \n**[[John Rowlands (author)|John Rowlands]], novelist and academic, 76<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-31588188  Welsh author John Rowlands dies, 76]</ref>\n**[[Dave Williams (Welsh footballer)|Dave Williams]], footballer, 72\n*[[24 February]] (date body discovered) \u2013 [[Roger Cecil]], painter, 72<ref>[http://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/gwentnews/11815937.Man_found_dead_believed_to_be_missing_man_and_renowned_artist_Roger_Cecil/?ref=rss  Man found dead believed to be missing man and renowned artist Roger Cecil - 'One of Wales\u2019 most accomplished artists']</ref>\n*[[6 March]] \u2013 [[Osi Rhys Osmond]], painter and television presenter, 71<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/31782981 Welsh artist and lecturer Osi Rhys Osmond dies]</ref>\n*[[11 March]] \u2013 [[Harri Pritchard Jones]], author, 81<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-31842541  BBC News, \"Writer Harri 